{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17533330","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17533330"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:35:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:35:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14779"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14779","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14779"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.51,0.06,0.26,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7470"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58556"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7470"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14779"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43958"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"255"},{"type":"tags","id":"702"},{"type":"tags","id":"2067"},{"type":"tags","id":"2544"},{"type":"tags","id":"2551"},{"type":"tags","id":"4632"},{"type":"tags","id":"4897"},{"type":"tags","id":"5593"},{"type":"tags","id":"5595"},{"type":"tags","id":"5604"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18282"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58556","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58556"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman is admitted to hospital for elective laparoscopic cholecystectomy. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. During emergence from general anaesthesia, she develops sudden onset stridor and chest wall retractions. Her oxygen saturation rapidly drops from 100% to 85%. On examination, there is no air movement despite respiratory effort, and no breath sounds are audible. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 165/95 mmHg, and SpO2 82% on an FiO2 of 100% via Hudson mask.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nasopharyngeal airway insertion","Endotracheal intubation","Intravenous dexamethasone","Continuous positive airway pressure","Nebulised adrenaline"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of laryngospasm during emergence from anaesthesia. Laryngospasm is a potentially life-threatening condition where the vocal cords spasm and close reflexively following the stimulation of extubation. It is characterised by signs of partial to complete obstruction such as stridor, absence of air movement, and rapidly decreasing oxygen saturation. The immediate priority is to break the laryngospasm and restore airway patency to allow oxygenation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuous positive airway pressure\u003C/strong\u003E with 100% oxygen via a tight-fitting face mask is the first-line treatment for laryngospasm. This technique can help break the spasm by applying steady positive pressure against the closed glottis to try and force the cords open.  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndotracheal intubation\u003C/strong\u003E may eventually be necessary if other measures fail, but it is not the first-line treatment as it may be technically difficult during active laryngospasm and could worsen the situation. It should be reserved for cases that don\u0027t respond to less invasive measures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENebulised adrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E would not be effective in this situation as the medication would not reach the larynx due to the complete airway obstruction. It is more appropriate for conditions like croup where there is partial upper airway obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous dexamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E may help reduce airway inflammation but takes hours to work and therefore is not appropriate for immediate management of acute complete airway obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENasopharyngeal airway insertion\u003C/strong\u003E would not help in this situation as the obstruction is at the level of the larynx, not in the upper airway. It could potentially stimulate the airway further and worsen the laryngospasm.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Laryngospasm is a protective reflex that can cause complete airway obstruction requiring immediate intervention.","Continuous positive airway pressure with a tight-fitting face mask is the first-line treatment for laryngospasm."],"references":["Rutt AL, Bojaxhi E, Torp KD. Management of Refractory Laryngospasm. J Voice. 2021 Jul;35(4):633-635. doi: 10.1016/j.jvoice.2020.01.004. Epub 2020 Jan 24. PMID: 31987708.","Visvanathan T, Kluger MT, Webb RK, et al. Crisis management during anaesthesia: laryngospasm. BMJ Quality \u0026 Safety 2005;14:e3.","Gil Gavel, Robert WM Walker, Laryngospasm in anaesthesia, Continuing Education in Anaesthesia Critical Care \u0026 Pain, Volume 14, Issue 2, April 2014, Pages 47\u201351, https://doi.org/10.1093/bjaceaccp/mkt031"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43958"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14779"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43958"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-01T15:39:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-01T15:40:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7470"}},"content":{"data":{"type"